<author><name><![CDATA[Kasumi]]></name></author>
<updated>2011-12-13T21:18:17-07:00</updated>
<published>2011-12-13T21:18:17-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8406&amp;p=87509#p87509</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8406&amp;p=87509#p87509"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Making graphics on the Mac]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8406&amp;p=87509#p87509"><![CDATA[
Here's an image (From a GBA game, but whatever): <br /><img src="http://img221.imageshack.us/img221/1883/bothh.png" alt="Image" /><br /><br />The NES basically has two layers. There is a background layer (top left), and a sprite layer (top right). On NES, sprites are drawn on top of the background except in very special cases. You can see them together on the bottom. (I also moved mario and luigi to a higher spot so you could see that the map actually has height and depth.)<br /><br />These layers are like sheets of glass, or animation cels. I paint a background on one (top left). Then I paint Mario and luigi on one. (top right).<br /><br />Then I put the cel with the bros on top of the one with the background. There is no way I can have... say a part of Mario's body disappear behind the tree because Mario's body is always drawn whole, and the cel with his body is always placed on top of the cell with the tree.<br /><br />This is why you can't walk behind a building in Final Fantasy: <br /><img src="http://img835.imageshack.us/img835/4293/59567705.png" alt="Image" /><br />If you walked one square down, the hero would appear on the roof of the building, instead of behind it as expected! So they just don't let you walk there.<br /><br />Here's another example of what can't happen:<br /><img src="http://img338.imageshack.us/img338/7320/badk.png" alt="Image" /><br />Top left: Mario is next to a building.<br />Top Right: Mario has jumped to the right on the building ceiling.<br />Bottom left: Mario has walked north passed the edge of the ceiling. He falls and is partially behind it.<br />Bottom Right: What Mario would like on NES in the exact same spot.<br /><br />The problem isn't specific to isometric graphics exactly. But "square" graphics give a little more freedom. With square graphics, you have three possible locations to fall from a square high place. (You can walk south and fall in front of it, east and fall to the right of it, and west and fall to the left of it.) Only two sides of an isometric square high place are safe to fall from.<br /><br />Another issue with isometric, is that NES limits the colors by square portions of the background layer, so laying out isometric maps that use a lot of color is difficult. <br /><br />In any case, if you only wanted to do top down walking and not top down walking and jumping to higher places, none of these things really matter.<br /><br />But saying all that is probably worth no more than saying isometric is harder to do. Or to keep the map flat if you want jumping like Gremlins 2 does. One day I will learn to write posts instead of books.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3504">Kasumi</a> — Tue Dec 13, 2011 9:18 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
