That sort of thing would probably be doable, but your mention of Immortal reminds me of one other thing one probably shouldn't ask for with: Games where you can go behind the background. <br /><br />Isometric games (The graphical style used by <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E20jk5vgkdQ" class="postlink">Solstice</a> or Immortal) are generally out because of this. I actually used to think Solstice was MAGIC because it can do this. I figured out how it's done, and it really is cool. But difficult. Check out 0:39 of that video, and if you look closely you can see the character go behind the background a few times in the following few rooms. <br /><br />Imagine a situation like this:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">+=Walkable Ground<br />*=Higher Walkable ground<br />|=Wall<br />0 = impassable ground<br />********<br />********<br />****0000<br />****0000<br />****0000<br />||||0000<br />++++0000<br />++++0000<br /></div><br />That is fine, because even though the player can go higher, there's never a situation where he could both be standing on a lower part of the map AND have part of his body behind a higher part of the map.<br /><br />This however is bad:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">+++++<br />****+<br />****+<br />||||+<br />+++++<br /></div><br /><br />Let's see a character here:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&amp;&amp;= Character<br />&amp;&amp;<br /><br />+&amp;&amp;++<br />****+<br />****+<br />||||+<br />+++++<br /></div><br /><br />What he's doing is standing behind the high wall, (that's why there are only two &amp; symbols) which is difficult to do on NES.<br /><br />If that doesn't make sense, I'll make actual pictures.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3504">Kasumi</a> — Tue Dec 13, 2011 7:59 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
